# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: jim-clinton
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:jim-clinton/american-association-19th-century] The **American Association of Base Ball Clubs** (**AA**) was a professional baseball league that existed for 10 seasons from 1882 to 1891.
[src:jim-clinton/american-association-19th-century] Together with the National League (NL), founded in 1876, the AA participated in an early version of the World Series seven times versus the champion of the NL in an interleague championship playoff tournament.
[src:jim-clinton/american-association-19th-century] At the end of its run, several AA franchises joined the NL.
[src:jim-clinton/american-association-19th-century] After 1891, the NL existed alone, with each season's champions being awarded the Temple Cup (1894–1897).
[src:jim-clinton/american-association-19th-century] During its existence, the AA was often simply referred to as "the Association" in the media, in contrast to the NL, which was sometimes called "the League".
[src:jim-clinton/american-association-19th-century] It was also sometimes called the "Beer and Whiskey League".
[src:jim-clinton/american-association-19th-century] The American Association (AA) distinguished itself in several ways from what it considered to be the puritanical National League (NL).
[src:jim-clinton/american-association-19th-century] The new league established teams in what the NL leaders pejoratively called "river cities", including Pittsburgh, Cincinnati, Louisville and St.
[src:jim-clinton/american-association-19th-century] Louis, with the inherent implication of lower morality or social standards in those cities.
[src:jim-clinton/american-association-19th-century] In contrast to the NL, the AA offered cheaper ticket prices, Sunday games and alcoholic beverages to its patrons.
[src:jim-clinton/american-association-19th-century] On November 8, 1881, at the Gibson House in Cincinnati, it was decided that individual teams in the league-to-be would operate their own affairs and set their own admission prices, under an agreement called the "guarantee system".
[src:jim-clinton/american-association-19th-century] The NL at that time prohibited the sale of alcohol on its grounds, while the AA had no such restrictions, especially as several of its teams were backed by breweries and distilleries.
[src:jim-clinton/american-association-19th-century] The AA became known as "The Beer and Whiskey League", another pejorative term applied by NL owners, which did not seem to bother the fans of the Association's clubs.
[src:jim-clinton/american-association-19th-century] Beginning in 1884 and continuing through 1890, the champion of the AA met the champion of the NL in an early version of the World Series.
[src:jim-clinton/american-association-19th-century] These early Series were less organized than the modern version, with as few as three games played and as many as fifteen, and the contests of 1885 and 1890 ending in disputed ties.
[src:jim-clinton/american-association-19th-century] The NL won four of these Series, while the AA won only one, in 1886 when the St.
[src:jim-clinton/american-association-19th-century] Louis Cardinals) defeated the Chicago White Stockings (now the Chicago Cubs).
[src:jim-clinton/american-association-19th-century] Over its lifetime, the AA was weakened by several factors.
[src:jim-clinton/american-association-19th-century] One was the tendency of some of its teams to jump to the NL.
[src:jim-clinton/american-association-19th-century] The consistently stronger NL was in better position to survive adverse conditions.
[src:jim-clinton/american-association-19th-century] Some owners of AA teams also owned a NL team.
[src:jim-clinton/american-association-19th-century] The most significant blow to the AA was dealt by the Players' League, a third major league formed in 1890, which siphoned off talent and gate receipts.
[src:jim-clinton/american-association-19th-century] In a rare historical oddity, the Brooklyn Bridegrooms (now the Los Angeles Dodgers) won the league's championship and represented the AA in the 1889 World Series, switched to the NL during the off-season, and then repeated the same feat.
[src:jim-clinton/american-association-19th-century] No player who spent the majority of his career in the AA is in the baseball Hall of Fame, although Bid McPhee of the Cincinnati Reds played eight of his eighteen seasons in the AA before the Reds moved to the National League.
[src:jim-clinton/american-association-19th-century] The living legacy of the old Association is the group of teams that came over to the National League to stay.
[src:jim-clinton/american-association-19th-century] The Pirates moved to the NL after the 1886 season, the Bridegrooms/Dodgers and the Cincinnati Reds after the 1889 season, and the Browns/Cardinals after the American Association folded following the 1891 season.
[src:jim-clinton/american-association-19th-century] Following the reorganization and contraction of the NL from 12 teams down to 8 in 1900, half of the eight surviving teams were former members of the AA.
[src:jim-clinton/american-association-19th-century] Several of the AA's home-field venues survived into the 1960s: The ballpark used by the 1891 Washington club evolved into Griffith Stadium; the home of the St.
[src:jim-clinton/american-association-19th-century] Louis Browns, Sportsman's Park; and the city block occupied by the Reds, which evolved into Crosley Field.
[src:jim-clinton/american-association-19th-century] Other than the clubs themselves, Crosley Field was the last physical remnant of the AA—it was the home field of the Cincinnati Reds until mid-season 1970 and was razed in April 1972.
[src:jim-clinton/american-association-19th-century] During the AA's existence, four clubs defected over to the NL: Allegheny City (joined NL 1887, later became the Pittsburgh Pirates), the Cleveland Spiders (joined NL 1889), the Brooklyn Bridegrooms (joined NL 1890, eventually renamed the Dodgers), and the Cincinnati Reds (joined NL 1890).
[src:jim-clinton/american-association-19th-century] At the AA's demise in 1891, four additional clubs joined the NL: the St.
[src:jim-clinton/american-association-19th-century] Louis Browns (later the Cardinals), the Louisville Colonels, the Washington Statesmen (renamed the Senators), and the Baltimore Orioles.
[src:jim-clinton/american-association-19th-century] Therefore, from 1892 to 1899, when the NL consisted of 12 teams, 8 of them had been former AA clubs.
[src:jim-clinton/american-association-19th-century] All four have posted more than 10,000 all-time major-league victories.
[src:jim-clinton/american-association-19th-century] AA statistics are recognized by Major League Baseball (MLB), the AA being one of six leagues deemed "major" by the Special Baseball Records Committee of Major League Baseball in 1969.
[src:jim-clinton/american-association-19th-century] The first line is the formation of the American Association (AA) in 1882, and the second marks the end of the American Association.
[src:jim-clinton/american-association-19th-century] World's Championship Series championships are shown with a "•", American Association Pennants in non-World Championship Series seasons are shown with a "#", and American Association Pennant winners who tied or lost the World Championship Series are shown with a "^".
[src:jim-clinton/american-association-19th-century] For the 1891 season, the Philadelphia Athletics were replaced by the Philadelphia Quakers of the Player's League.
[src:jim-clinton/american-association-19th-century] The 1891 Cincinnati Kelly's Killers folded during the season and were replaced by the Milwaukee Brewers.
[src:jim-clinton/american-association-19th-century] All non-American Association labels not labeled "NL" (National League) or "PL" (Players' League) are minor league teams.
[src:jim-clinton/baltimore-orioles-19th-century] The **Baltimore Orioles** were a 19th-century professional baseball team that competed from 1882 to 1899, first in the American Association and later in the National League.
[src:jim-clinton/baltimore-orioles-19th-century] Despite their success, the dominant Orioles were contracted out of the National League after the 1899 season, when the league reduced in size from 12 members to eight.
[src:jim-clinton/baltimore-orioles-19th-century] Most of the Orioles' best players moved to the Brooklyn Superbas—Baltimore owner Harry Von der Horst also had an ownership stake in Brooklyn.
[src:jim-clinton/baltimore-orioles-19th-century] Upon the foundation of the American League in 1901, a reorganized Baltimore Orioles franchise competed as a charter member for two seasons, before folding and being replaced by the New York Highlanders, later renamed the New York Yankees.
[src:jim-clinton/baltimore-orioles-19th-century] The team, formally the "Baltimore Base Ball and Exhibition Company", was founded in 1882 as a charter member of the American Association (AA), considered a major league.
[src:jim-clinton/baltimore-orioles-19th-century] The Orioles finished last in the league in four of their first five season, the exception being a sixth-place finish in 1884 when 13 different teams played in the league.
[src:jim-clinton/baltimore-orioles-19th-century] The team then had its best positional finish, third place, in 1887, followed by two seasons finishing fifth in the then eight-team league.
[src:jim-clinton/baltimore-orioles-19th-century] The Orioles dropped out of the league after the 1889 season, and began the 1890 season playing in the minor-league Atlantic Association.
[src:jim-clinton/baltimore-orioles-19th-century] However, when the last-place Brooklyn Gladiators of the AA folded in late August, the Orioles re-joined the AA and played 38 games to complete the 1890 season, posting a record of 15–19 with four ties.
[src:jim-clinton/baltimore-orioles-19th-century] The Orioles remained in the AA for 1891, finishing sixth among nine teams in the AA's final season.
[src:jim-clinton/baltimore-orioles-19th-century] Overall, during 10 seasons of AA play, the Orioles had a cumulative record of 489–602 (.448).
[src:jim-clinton/baltimore-orioles-19th-century] The Orioles were one of four AA clubs (the others being the Louisville Colonels, St.
[src:jim-clinton/baltimore-orioles-19th-century] Louis Browns, and Washington Statesmen) merged into the National League (NL) in 1892, formally as a 12-member "League Association".
[src:jim-clinton/baltimore-orioles-19th-century] The beginnings of the team can be traced to June 1892, when owner Harry Von der Horst hired Ned Hanlon to be manager of the Orioles, giving him stock in the team and full authority over baseball operations.
[src:jim-clinton/baltimore-orioles-19th-century] Hanlon moved his growing family to a house that stood a block away from the team's ballpark.
[src:jim-clinton/baltimore-orioles-19th-century] After finishing last in the league in 1892 and eighth in 1893, the Orioles won three consecutive pennants during 1894–1896, featuring several future Hall of Famers under manager Hanlon.
[src:jim-clinton/baltimore-orioles-19th-century] They followed up the title run with two second-place finishes, in 1897 and 1898.
[src:jim-clinton/baltimore-orioles-19th-century] Accordingly, they participated in all four editions of the post-season Temple Cup series, held from 1894 through 1897 between the NL's top two teams, winning in 1896 and 1897.
[src:jim-clinton/baltimore-orioles-19th-century] After the team's 1898 second-place finish, most of the team's stars were moved to the Brooklyn Bridegrooms, who were renamed as the Superbas for 1899 and eventually became known as the Dodgers.
[src:jim-clinton/baltimore-orioles-19th-century] The players moved when Von der Horst and Hanlon became part owners of the Brooklyn team, with Hanlon also becoming Brooklyn's manager.
[src:jim-clinton/baltimore-orioles-19th-century] Third baseman John McGraw and catcher Wilbert Robinson remained in Baltimore, with McGraw remaining as first-year player-manager.
[src:jim-clinton/baltimore-orioles-19th-century] Following a fourth-place finish in 1899, the Orioles were one of four clubs eliminated by the NL (the others being the Cleveland Spiders, Louisville Colonels, and the aforementioned Washington Statesmen, then known as the Washington Senators).
[src:jim-clinton/baltimore-orioles-19th-century] During their eight seasons of play in the NL, the Orioles compiled an overall record of 644–447 (.590).
[src:jim-clinton/baltimore-orioles-19th-century] In the eight-team NL of 1900, McGraw and Robinson joined the St.
[src:jim-clinton/baltimore-orioles-19th-century] In 1901, McGraw followed through on his threats to abandon the NL and form a club in the rival American League (AL), being formed by new president Ban Johnson out of the former minor-league Western League.
[src:jim-clinton/baltimore-orioles-19th-century] These newly formed Orioles of the AL only stayed in Baltimore for two seasons.
[src:jim-clinton/baltimore-orioles-19th-century] In 1903, a team was established in New York City as "the price of peace" as agreement between the older circuit (the NL) and its new upstart rival (the AL) allowing the "Americans" to have a team based in the city as a sign of respectability.
[src:jim-clinton/baltimore-orioles-19th-century] The AL team in New York became known as the New York Highlanders (or occasionally the New York Americans), later renamed in 1913 as the New York Yankees.
[src:jim-clinton/baltimore-orioles-19th-century] The Yankees do not consider the 1901–1902 Baltimore team as part of their history.
[src:jim-clinton/baltimore-orioles-19th-century] In 1903, an Orioles franchise in the old minor-league Eastern League filled the void left by the departure of the major-league Orioles.
[src:jim-clinton/baltimore-orioles-19th-century] These minor-league Orioles included local product and future baseball icon Babe Ruth and Lefty Grove.
[src:jim-clinton/baltimore-orioles-19th-century] The team won a string of seven straight titles, 1919–1925, at the then highest level of the minor leagues in the reorganized International League (known as such from 1912 onward).
[src:jim-clinton/baltimore-orioles-19th-century] A major-league franchise did not return to Baltimore until the St.
[src:jim-clinton/baltimore-orioles-19th-century] Louis Browns (not the Browns of the AA, but a team that had its origins in Milwaukee) relocated to the city in 1954 and was renamed as the current Baltimore Orioles of Major League Baseball.
[src:jim-clinton/baltimore-orioles-19th-century] The Orioles of the American Association first played at Newington Park for the 1882 season.
[src:jim-clinton/baltimore-orioles-19th-century] Starting in 1883, the team played at the old Oriole Park, in Harwood, south of the Waverly neighborhood at 29th and Barclay Streets, just a block west from Greenmount Avenue, remaining there into the 1891 season.
[src:jim-clinton/baltimore-orioles-19th-century] The 1901–1902 American League team played at Oriole Park a decade later.
[src:jim-clinton/baltimore-orioles-19th-century] During the 1891 season, the Orioles moved a few blocks away to Union Park on Huntington Avenue (later renamed 25th Street) and Greenmount Avenue.
[src:jim-clinton/baltimore-orioles-19th-century] The team remained at Union Park for its entire time in the National League, 1892 through 1899.
[src:jim-clinton/baltimore-orioles-19th-century] The original Orioles were one of the most storied teams in the history of the game.
[src:jim-clinton/baltimore-orioles-19th-century] Managed by Ned Hanlon, they won NL pennants in 1894, 1895, and 1896, and sported some of the most colorful players in history including John McGraw, Wee Willie Keeler, Hughie Jennings, Joe Kelley, Wilbert Robinson, and Dan Brouthers.
[src:jim-clinton/baltimore-orioles-19th-century] They were rough characters who practically invented "scientific" baseball, the form of baseball played before the home run became the norm in the 1920s.
[src:jim-clinton/baltimore-orioles-19th-century] Like the style known today as "small ball", the "inside baseball" strategy of Orioles featured tight pitching, hit and run tactics, stolen bases, and precise bunting.
[src:jim-clinton/baltimore-orioles-19th-century] One such play, where the batter deliberately strikes the pitched ball downward onto the infield surface with sufficient force such that the ball rebounds skyward, allowing the batter to reach first base safely before the opposing team can field the ball, remains known as a Baltimore chop.
[src:jim-clinton/baltimore-orioles-19th-century] Matt Kilroy pitched a no-hitter for the Orioles on October 6, 1886; Bill Hawke threw one on August 16, 1893, the first from the modern pitching distance of 60 feet, 6 inches; and Jay Hughes threw a no-hitter for the Orioles on April 22, 1898.
[src:jim-clinton/baseball-reference] Founder Sean Forman began developing the website while working on his Ph.D. dissertation in applied math and computational science at the University of Iowa.
[src:jim-clinton/baseball-reference] While writing his dissertation, he had also been writing articles on and blogging about sabermetrics.
[src:jim-clinton/baseball-reference] Forman's database was originally built from the *Total Baseball* series of baseball encyclopedias.
[src:jim-clinton/baseball-reference] The website went online in April 2000, after first being launched in February 2000 as part of the website for the *Big Bad Baseball Annual*.
[src:jim-clinton/baseball-reference] It was originally built as a web interface to the Lahman Baseball Database, though it now employs a variety of data sources.
[src:jim-clinton/baseball-reference] In 2004, Forman founded Sports Reference.
[src:jim-clinton/baseball-reference] Sports Reference is a website that came out of the Baseball Reference website.
[src:jim-clinton/baseball-reference] The company was incorporated as Sports Reference, LLC in 2007.
[src:jim-clinton/baseball-reference] In 2006, Forman left his job as a math professor at Saint Joseph's University to focus on Baseball Reference full-time.
[src:jim-clinton/baseball-reference] In February 2009, Fantasy Sports Ventures took a minority stake in Sports Reference, for a "low seven-figure sum".
[src:jim-clinton/baseball-reference] In late April 2021, the site changed a number of identifying names, "discontinuing the use of nicknames that are racially or ethnically influenced" and "names based upon a player's disability", such as Chief Bender and Dummy Hoy, who are now listed as Charles Bender and Billy Hoy, respectively.
[src:jim-clinton/baseball-reference] To compare ballplayers to one-another it offers "Black Ink" and "Gray Ink" tests, which tally a player's dominance and overall productivity against his peers.
[src:jim-clinton/baseball-reference] In 2012, it began to offer Jay Jaffe's Jaffe Wins Above Replacement Score (JAWS) statistic for comparing players of different eras against each other by weighing their performance in the prime as well as their entire career.
[src:jim-clinton/baseball-reference] Baseball Reference began including its version of Wins Above Replacement (WAR) in 2010.
[src:jim-clinton/baseball-reference] Its version determining a player's value differs slightly from other baseball statistics websites, including FanGraphs and Baseball Prospectus.
[src:jim-clinton/baseball-reference] Baseball Reference has its own baseball encyclopedia, a wiki called "Baseball Reference Bullpen", which can be edited by anyone and is modeled after Wikipedia.
[src:jim-clinton/baseball-reference] As of November 2025, the Bullpen contains more than 123,000 articles.
[src:jim-clinton/batting-average-baseball] In baseball, **batting average** (**BA**) is determined by dividing a player's hits by their total at-bats.
[src:jim-clinton/batting-average-baseball] It is usually rounded to three decimal places and read without the decimal: A player with a batting average of .300 is said to be "batting three hundred".
[src:jim-clinton/batting-average-baseball] If necessary to break ties, batting averages could be taken beyond the .001 measurement.
[src:jim-clinton/batting-average-baseball] In this context, .001 is considered a "point", such that a .235 batter is five points higher than a .230 batter.
[src:jim-clinton/batting-average-baseball] Henry Chadwick, an English statistician raised on cricket, was an influential figure in the early history of baseball.
[src:jim-clinton/batting-average-baseball] He is credited with creating the modern box score, in 1859, and the practice of denoting a strikeout with a "K".
[src:jim-clinton/batting-average-baseball] In 1869, another early baseball proponent, Alfred Wright, published an end-of-season summary that included the average number of times a batter had "clean" hits on a *per game* basis.
[src:jim-clinton/batting-average-baseball] In 1871, a writer for the *New York Clipper*, Hervie Dobson, proposed that a batter's "average is found by dividing his total 'times first base on clean hits' by his total number of times he went to the bat"—hits divided by at bats.
[src:jim-clinton/batting-average-baseball] By 1874, some teams were calculating batting averages, and by 1876, it was being calculated by all teams of the National League.
[src:jim-clinton/batting-average-baseball] In modern times, a season batting average of .300 or higher is considered to be excellent, and an average higher than .400 is a nearly unachievable goal.
[src:jim-clinton/batting-average-baseball] The last Major League Baseball (MLB) player to do so, with enough plate appearances to qualify for the batting championship, was Ted Williams of the Boston Red Sox, who hit .406 in 1941.
[src:jim-clinton/batting-average-baseball] Note that batting averages are rounded; entering the final day of the 1941 season, Williams was at 179-for-448, which is .39955 and would have been recorded as .400 via rounding.
[src:jim-clinton/batting-average-baseball] However, Williams played in both games of a doubleheader, went 6-for-8, and ended the season 185-for-456, which is .40570 and becomes .406 when rounded.
[src:jim-clinton/batting-average-baseball] Since 1941, no American League or National League player has hit .400 or above—the highest single-season average in those leagues has been .394 by Tony Gwynn of the San Diego Padres in 1994.
[src:jim-clinton/batting-average-baseball] Wade Boggs hit .401 over a 162-game span with Boston from June 9, 1985, to June 6, 1986, but never hit above .368 for an MLB season.
[src:jim-clinton/batting-average-baseball] There have been numerous attempts to explain the disappearance of the .400 hitter, with one of the more rigorous discussions of this question appearing in Stephen Jay Gould's 1996 book *Full House*.
[src:jim-clinton/batting-average-baseball] Josh Gibson hit .466 in 1943 while playing for the Homestead Grays of the Negro National League, one of several leagues within Negro league baseball that are now recognized by MLB.
[src:jim-clinton/batting-average-baseball] Gibson holds the record for highest major-league career batting average at .371, four points higher than Ty Cobb, who has the second-highest career average at .367.
[src:jim-clinton/batting-average-baseball] The record for lowest career batting average for a player with more than 2,500 at-bats belongs to Bill Bergen, a catcher who played from 1901 to 1911 and recorded a .170 average in 3,028 career at-bats.
[src:jim-clinton/batting-average-baseball] Hugh Duffy, who played from 1888 to 1906, is credited with the highest single-season batting average, having hit .440 in 1894.
[src:jim-clinton/batting-average-baseball] The modern-era (post-1900) record for highest batting average for a season is held by Nap Lajoie, who hit .426 in 1901, the first year of play for the American League.
[src:jim-clinton/batting-average-baseball] The modern-era record for the lowest batting average for a player that qualified for the batting title is held by Chris Davis, who hit .168 in 2018.
[src:jim-clinton/batting-average-baseball] While finishing six plate appearances short of qualifying for the batting title, Adam Dunn of the Chicago White Sox hit .159 for the 2011 season, nine points lower than the record.
[src:jim-clinton/batting-average-baseball] The highest batting average for a rookie was .408 in 1911 by Shoeless Joe Jackson.
[src:jim-clinton/batting-average-baseball] The league batting average in MLB for the 2018 season was .248, with the highest modern-era MLB average being .296 in 1930, and the lowest being .237 in 1968.
[src:jim-clinton/batting-average-baseball] For non-pitchers, a batting average below .230 is often considered poor, and one below .200 is usually unacceptable.
[src:jim-clinton/batting-average-baseball] This latter level is sometimes referred to as "The Mendoza Line", named for Mario Mendoza—a lifetime .215 hitter but a good defensive shortstop.
[src:jim-clinton/batting-average-baseball] Sabermetrics, the study of baseball statistics, considers batting average a weak measure of performance because it does not correlate as well as other measures to runs scored, thereby causing it to have little predictive value.
[src:jim-clinton/batting-average-baseball] Batting average does not take into account bases on balls (walks) or power, whereas other statistics such as on-base percentage and slugging percentage have been specifically designed to measure such concepts.
[src:jim-clinton/batting-average-baseball] Adding these statistics together form a player's on-base plus slugging or "OPS".
[src:jim-clinton/batting-average-baseball] This is commonly seen as a much better, though not perfect, indicator of a player's overall batting ability as it is a measure of hitting for average, hitting for power, and drawing walks.
[src:jim-clinton/batting-average-baseball] In 1887, bases on balls (walks) were counted as hits by the major leagues in existence at the time.
[src:jim-clinton/batting-average-baseball] This inflated batting averages, with 11 players batting .400 or better, and the experiment was abandoned the following season.
[src:jim-clinton/batting-average-baseball] In rare instances, players have concluded their careers with a perfect batting average of 1.000—through the 2021 season, there were 94 such players in major-league history, 83 of whom recorded exactly one hit in one at bat.
[src:jim-clinton/batting-average-baseball] Only one player with a 1.000 average has had three hits—outfielder John Paciorek (1963), who had three hits in three at bats; he also had two walks, and scored four runs.
[src:jim-clinton/batting-average-baseball] Players who had two hits in their only two at bats include: pitcher Frank O'Connor (1893), catcher Mike Hopkins (1902), pitcher Doc Tonkin (1907), pitcher Hal Deviney (1920), pitcher Fred Schemanske (1923), pitcher Chet Kehn (1942), second baseman Steve Biras (1944), and pitcher Jason Roach (2003).
[src:jim-clinton/batting-average-baseball] Pitcher Esteban Yan, who played in 472 major-league games from 1996 to 2006, mainly in the American League (where pitchers have rarely batted since the introduction of the designated hitter in 1973), also had two hits in his only two at bats, one a home run.
[src:jim-clinton/batting-average-baseball] The MLB batting averages championships (often referred to as "the batting title") are awarded annually to the player in each league with the highest batting average.
[src:jim-clinton/batting-average-baseball] Ty Cobb holds the MLB and American League (AL) record for most batting titles, officially winning 11 in his career.
[src:jim-clinton/batting-average-baseball] The National League (NL) record of eight batting titles is shared by Honus Wagner and Tony Gwynn.
[src:jim-clinton/batting-average-baseball] This is officially Rule 10.22(a), but it is also known as the "Tony Gwynn rule" because the Padres' player won the batting crown in 1996 with a .353 average on just 498 plate appearances (i.e., he was four short).
[src:jim-clinton/batting-average-baseball] Gwynn was awarded the title since he would have led the league even if he had gone 0-for-4 in those missing plate appearances.
[src:jim-clinton/batting-average-baseball] His average would have dropped to .349, five points better than second-place Ellis Burks' .344.
[src:jim-clinton/batting-average-baseball] In 2012, a one-time amendment to the rule was made to disqualify Melky Cabrera from the title.
[src:jim-clinton/batting-average-baseball] Cabrera requested that he be disqualified after serving a suspension that season for a positive testosterone test.
[src:jim-clinton/batting-average-baseball] He had batted .346 with 501 plate appearances, and the original rule would have awarded him the title over San Francisco Giants teammate Buster Posey, who won batting .336.
[src:jim-clinton/batting-average-baseball] The highest recorded single-season batting average in Minor League Baseball is .462, accomplished by Gary Redus in 1978, when he played for the Billings Mustangs, an affiliate of the Cincinnati Reds in the Rookie Advanced-level Pioneer League.
[src:jim-clinton/batting-average-baseball] Redus was 117-for-253 in 68 games, as the Pioneer League only plays from June to early September.
[src:jim-clinton/batting-average-baseball] Redus went on to play in MLB from 1982 through 1994, batting .252 during his MLB career.
[src:jim-clinton/batting-average-baseball] In Nippon Professional Baseball (NPB), the leader in career batting average is Isao Harimoto, a member of the Japanese Baseball Hall of Fame, who hit .319 in his NPB career.
[src:jim-clinton/batting-average-baseball] Ichiro Suzuki batted .353 in NPB, but does not have enough NPB career at-bats to qualify for the league's title.
[src:jim-clinton/batting-average-baseball] Sadaharu Oh had a batting average of .355 in 1973 season.
[src:jim-clinton/batting-average-baseball] Randy Bass had a batting average of .389 in 1986 season.
[src:jim-clinton/batting-average-baseball] In KBO League (KBO), the leader in career batting average is Jung-hoo Lee, who hit .340 in his KBO career and is currently an active player.
[src:jim-clinton/batting-average-baseball] Baek In-chun had a batting average of .412 in 1982 season.
[src:jim-clinton/batting-average-baseball] This is the highest batting average of one season in KBO League.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] Founded in 1871 during the Reconstruction era, Birmingham was formed through the merger of three smaller communities, most notably Elyton.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] It quickly grew into an industrial and transportation center, with a focus on mining, steel production, and railroads.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] Named for Birmingham, England, it developed with a labor force that included many African Americans from rural Alabama, often employed under non-union conditions.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] The Birmingham area serves as headquarters to Fortune 500 companies Regions Financial and Vulcan Materials Company, along with multiple other Fortune 1000 companies.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] The University of Alabama at Birmingham, established in 1969, includes a prominent medical school, dental school, and other professional programs, making it one of the state's leading research institutions.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] The area also hosts private colleges such as Samford University and Miles College, along with Jefferson State Community College and Lawson State Community College.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] Birmingham is also home to the headquarters of the Southeastern Conference (SEC) and Southwestern Athletic Conference (SWAC), reinforcing its cultural and athletic influence in the region.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] The Birmingham area was historically part of the territory of the Muscogee Confederacy.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] The most prominent Indigenous settlement in the area in the 19th century was the Upper Creek community of *Tvlwv Haco*, meaning 'Crazy Town' in Muscogee, located in present-day Indian Springs Village.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] Birmingham was founded on June 1, 1871, by the Elyton Land Company whose investors included cotton planters, bankers and railroad entrepreneurs.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] It was named for the English city of Birmingham, the United Kingdom's second largest city.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] Most of the original settlers who founded Birmingham were of English ancestry.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] The Elyton Land Company sold lots near the planned crossing of the Alabama & Chattanooga and South & North Alabama railroads, including land formerly a part of the Benjamin P.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] The first business at that crossroads was the trading post and country store operated by Marre & Allen.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] The site of the railroad crossing was notable for the nearby deposits of iron ore, coal, and limestone – the three main raw materials used in making steel.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] The Birmingham District is the only place worldwide where significant amounts of all three minerals can be found in close proximity.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] From the start the new city was planned as a great center of industry.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] The founders, organized as the Elyton Land Company, borrowed the name of Birmingham, one of England's main industrial cities, to advertise that point.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] The growth of the planned city was impeded by an outbreak of cholera, and a Wall Street crash in 1873.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] However, it began to develop shortly afterwards at an explosive rate.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] In 1911, the town of Elyton and several other surrounding towns were absorbed into Birmingham.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] The start of the 20th century brought the substantial growth that gave Birmingham the nickname "The Magic City", as the downtown area developed from a low-rise commercial and residential district into a busy grid of neoclassical mid-rise and high-rise buildings and busy streetcar lines.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] Between 1902 and 1912 four large office buildings were constructed at the intersection of 20th Street, the central north–south spine of the city, and 1st Avenue North, which connected the warehouses and industrial facilities stretching along the east–west railroad corridor.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] This impressive group of early skyscrapers was nicknamed "The Heaviest Corner on Earth".
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] In 1916, Birmingham was hit by the Irondale earthquake, with a 5.1 magnitude.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] A few buildings in the area were slightly damaged.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] The earthquake was felt as far as Atlanta and neighboring states.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] While excluded from the best-paying industrial jobs, Black Americans joined the migration of residents from rural areas to the city for its opportunities.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] The Great Depression of the 1930s hit Birmingham especially hard as sources of capital that were fueling the city's growth rapidly dried up at the same time that farm laborers, driven off the land, made their way to the city in search of work.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] New Deal programs put many city residents to work in WPA and CCC programs, making important contributions to the city's infrastructure and artistic legacy, including such key improvements as Vulcan's tower and Oak Mountain State Park.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] The wartime demand for steel and the post-war building boom gave Birmingham a rapid return to prosperity.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] Manufacturing diversified beyond the production of raw materials.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] Major civic institutions such as schools, parks and museums, were able to expand their scope.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] Despite the growing population and wealth of the city, its residents were markedly underrepresented in the state legislature.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] Although the state constitution required redistricting in accordance with changes in the decennial census, the state legislature did not undertake this until the early 1970s, when forced by a federal court case to enforce "one man, one vote".
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] In addition, the geographic basis of the senate, which gave each county one seat, gave undue influence to rural counties.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] Representatives of rural counties also had disproportionate power in the state house, and failed to provide support for infrastructure and other improvements in developing urban population centers such as Birmingham.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] At this time, the General Assembly ran county governments as extensions of the state through their legislative delegations.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] In the 1950s and 1960s Birmingham received national and international attention as a center of the civil rights struggle for African-Americans.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] Locally the movement's activists were led by Fred Shuttlesworth, a fiery preacher who became legendary for his fearlessness in the face of violence, notably a string of racially motivated bombings that earned Birmingham the derisive nickname "Bombingham".
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] A watershed in the civil rights movement occurred in 1963 when Shuttlesworth requested that Martin Luther King Jr., and the Southern Christian Leadership Conference (SCLC), which Shuttlesworth had co-founded, come to Birmingham, where King had once been a pastor, to help end segregation.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] Together they launched "Project C" (for "Confrontation"), a massive assault on the Jim Crow system.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] In April and May daily mass marches organized and led by movement leader James Bevel were met with police repression, tear gas, attack dogs, fire hoses, and arrests.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] More than 3,000 people were arrested during these protests, almost all of them high-school age children.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] These protests were ultimately successful, leading not only to desegregation of public accommodation in Birmingham but also to the Civil Rights Act of 1964.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] While imprisoned for having taken part in a nonviolent protest, Dr.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] King wrote the now famous April 16 Letter from Birmingham Jail, a defining treatise in his cause against segregation.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] Birmingham is also known for the September 15 incident, in which four black girls were killed by a bomb planted at the 16th Street Baptist Church.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] The event would inspire the African-American poet Dudley Randall's opus, "The Ballad of Birmingham", as well as jazz musician John Coltrane's song "Alabama".
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] In 1998, the Birmingham Pledge, which local attorney James Rotch wrote, was introduced at the Martin Luther King Unity Breakfast.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] As a grassroots community commitment to combating racism and prejudice, it has since then been used for programs in all fifty states and in more than twenty countries.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] In the 1970s, urban-renewal efforts focused around the development of the University of Alabama at Birmingham, which developed into a major medical and research center.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] In 1971, Birmingham celebrated its centennial with a round of public-works improvements, including an upgrade of Vulcan Park and the construction of a major downtown convention center containing a 2,500-seat symphony hall, theater, 19,000-seat arena, and exhibition halls.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] Birmingham's banking institutions enjoyed considerable growth as well and new skyscrapers started to appear in the city center for the first time since the 1920s.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] These projects helped diversify the city's economy but did not prevent the exodus of many of the city's residents to nearby independent suburbs.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] Richard Arrington Jr. as its first African-American mayor.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] The population inside Birmingham's city limits has fallen over the past few decades, due in large part to "white flight" from the city of Birmingham proper to surrounding suburbs.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] The city's formerly most populous ethnic group, non-Hispanic white, has declined from 57.4 percent in 1970 to 21.1 percent in 2010.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] From its highest population of 340,887 in 1960, the population was down to 200,733 in 2020, a loss of about 41 percent.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] That same period saw a corresponding rise in the populations of the suburban communities of Hoover, Vestavia Hills, Alabaster, and Gardendale, none of which were incorporated as municipalities until after 1950.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] In 2006, the city's visitors bureau selected "the diverse city" as a new tag line for the city.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] In 2011, the American Planning Association named the Highland Park neighborhood of Birmingham as a 2011 America's Great Place.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] In 2015, the International World Game Executive Committee selected Birmingham over Lima, Peru and Ufa, Russia, for the 2021 World Games, but the COVID-19 pandemic delayed the event by a year.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] After the 2020 census, Birmingham lost its long-standing status as Alabama's largest city, with Huntsville overtaking Birmingham in total population, though Birmingham remains the state's largest metropolitan area.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] Birmingham hosted the 2022 World Games in July 2022.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] In September 2024 a mass shooting occurred in Birmingham, killing four people.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] Birmingham occupies Jones Valley, flanked by long parallel mountain ridges (the tailing ends of the Appalachian foothills – see Ridge-and-Valley Appalachians) running from north-east to south-west.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] The valley is drained by small creeks (Village Creek, Valley Creek) which flow into the Black Warrior River.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] The valley was bisected by the principal railroad corridor, along which most of the early manufacturing operations began.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] Red Mountain lies immediately south of downtown.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] Many of Birmingham's television and radio broadcast towers are lined up along this prominent ridge.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] The "Over the Mountain" area, including Shades Valley, Shades Mountain and beyond, was largely shielded from the industrial smoke and rough streets of the industrial city.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] This is the setting for Birmingham's more affluent suburbs of Mountain Brook, Vestavia Hills, Homewood, and Hoover.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] South of Shades Valley is the Cahaba River basin, one of the most diverse river ecosystems in the United States.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] Sand Mountain, a smaller ridge, flanks the city to the north and divides Jones Valley from much more rugged land to the north.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] The Louisville and Nashville Railroad (now CSX Transportation) enters the valley through Boyles Gap, a prominent gap in the long low ridge.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] Ruffner Mountain, located due east of the heart of the city, is home to Ruffner Mountain Nature Center, one of the largest urban nature reserves in the United States.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] Census Bureau, the city has a total area of 151.9 square miles (393 km2), of which, 149.9 square miles (388 km2) is land and 2.0 square miles (5.2 km2) (1.34%) is water.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] Most of the metropolitan area lies outside of the city itself.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] According to the US Census Bureau, the Birmingham area consists of 7 counties and over 100 suburbs.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] The population of the area as of the 2020 census was 1,180,631.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] Some argue that the region suffers from having too many suburbs because companies can receive large incentives to move a short distance to another city, with no net gain in the area's economy.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] Birmingham has a humid subtropical climate, characterized by hot summers, mild winters, and abundant rainfall.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] Birmingham is primarily in USDA Hardiness Zone 8a, with some neighborhoods in Zone 8b.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] January has a daily mean temperature of 43.8 °F (6.6 °C).
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] There are an average of 47 days annually with a low at or below freezing, and 1.4 days where the high does not surpass freezing.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] July has a daily mean temperature of 81.1 °F (27.3 °C).
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] Highs reach or exceed 90 °F (32 °C) on 65 days per year and 100 °F (38 °C) on 2.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] Precipitation is relatively well-distributed throughout the year, sometimes falling in the form of snow during winter.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] 10.3 inches (26.2 cm) fell on March 13, 1993, during the 1993 Storm of the Century, which established the highest daily snowfall, one-storm, and winter season total on record.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] For the same period, the median monthly snowfall for each month was zero.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] The summer months are hot, with high humidity.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] Most of the precipitation that falls in the summer are from thunderstorms, most of which occur in the afternoon and evening hours.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] The spring and fall months are pleasant but variable as cold fronts frequently bring strong to severe thunderstorms and occasional tornadoes to the region.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] The fall season (primarily October) features less rainfall and fewer storms, as well as lower humidity than the spring, but November and early December represent a secondary severe weather season.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] Birmingham is located in the heart of a Tornado Alley known as the Dixie Alley due to the high frequency of tornadoes in Central Alabama.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] The greater Birmingham area has been hit by two F5 tornadoes; one in Birmingham's northern suburbs in 1977, and second in the western suburbs in 1998.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] The area was hit by an EF4 tornado which was part of a larger outbreak in April 2011.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] In late summer and fall months, Birmingham experiences occasional tropical storms and hurricanes due to its proximity to the Central Gulf Coast.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] The record high temperature is 107 °F (42 °C), set on July 29, 1930.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] The Birmingham area is not prone to frequent earthquakes; its historical activity level is 59% less than the US average.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] Earthquakes are generally minor and the Birmingham area can feel an earthquake from the Eastern Tennessee Seismic Zone.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] The magnitude 5.1 Irondale earthquake in 1916 caused damage in the Birmingham area and was felt in the neighboring states and as far as the Carolinas.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] The 2003 Alabama earthquake centered in northeastern Alabama (magnitude 4.6–4.9) was also felt in Birmingham, Atlanta, Tennessee, Kentucky, and both Carolina states.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] Note: the US census treats Hispanic/Latino as an ethnic category.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] This table excludes Latinos from the racial categories and assigns them to a separate category.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] As of the 2020 census, Birmingham had a population of 200,733 — 89,976 households, and 46,816 families.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] 18.7% of residents were under the age of 18 and 16.6% of residents were 65 years of age or older.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] For every 100 females there were 86.8 males, and for every 100 females age 18 and over there were 83.4 males age 18 and over.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] 99.1% of residents lived in urban areas, while 0.9% lived in rural areas.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] There were 89,976 households in Birmingham, of which 21.8% had children under the age of 18 living in them.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] Of all households, 21.7% were married-couple households, 26.5% were households with a male householder and no spouse or partner present, and 45.3% were households with a female householder and no spouse or partner present.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] About 42.1% of all households were made up of individuals and 12.5% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] There were 106,713 housing units, of which 15.7% were vacant.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] The homeowner vacancy rate was 2.1% and the rental vacancy rate was 12.3%.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] In the 2000 census, there were 242,820 people, 98,782 households, and 59,269 families living in Birmingham.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] The population density was 1,619.7 inhabitants per square mile (625.4/km2).
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] There were 111,927 housing units at an average density of 746.6 per square mile (288.3/km2).
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] The racial makeup of the city was 62.46% Black, 35.07% White, 0.17% Native American, 0.80% Asian, 0.04% Pacific Islander, 0.62% from other races, and 0.83% from two or more races.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] 1.55% of the population were Hispanic or Latino of any race.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] There were 98,782 households, out of which 27.7% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 31.1% were married couples living together, 24.6% had a female householder with no husband present, and 40.0% were non-families.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] 34.4% of all households were made up of individuals, and 10.4% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] In Birmingham, 25.0% of the population was under the age of 18, 11.1% was from 18 to 24, 30.0% from 25 to 44, 20.4% from 45 to 64, and 13.5% was 65 years of age or older.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] For every 100 females there were 85.7 males.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] The median income for a household in the city was $31,898, and the median income for a family was $38,776.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] Males had a median income of $36,031 versus $30,367 for females.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] The city's per capita income was $19,962.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] About 22.5% of families and 27.3% of the population were below the poverty line, including 41.9% of those under the age of 18 and 18.3% of those age 65 or over.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] The Association of Statisticians of American Religious Bodies published data showing that in 2010, among metro areas with a greater than one million population, Birmingham had the second highest ratio of Christians, and the greatest ratio of Protestant adherents, in the United States.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] The Southern Baptist Convention has 673 congregations and 336,000 members in the Birmingham Metro area.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] The United Methodists have 196 congregations and 66,759 members.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] The headquarters of the Presbyterian Church in America had been in Birmingham until the early 1980s; the PCA has more than 30 congregations and almost 15,000 members in the Birmingham-Hoover Metropolitan area with megachurches like Briarwood Presbyterian Church.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] The National Baptist Convention has 126 congregations and 69,800 members.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] The city is home to the Roman Catholic Diocese of Birmingham, covering 39 counties and comprising 75 parishes and missions as well as seven Catholic high schools and nineteen elementary schools; there are also two Eastern Catholic parishes in the Birmingham area.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] The Catholic television network EWTN is headquartered in metropolitan Birmingham.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] There are three Eastern Orthodox Churches in the Metro Area as well, Greek, Russian and American.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] There is also a Unitarian Universalist church in the Birmingham area.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] The main campus of the Church of the Highlands is located in Birmingham.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] The church operates schools and churches across Alabama.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] From Birmingham's early days onward, the steel industry has always played a crucial role in the local economy.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] Though the steel industry no longer has the same prominence it once held in Birmingham, steel production and processing continue to play a key role in the economy.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] Steel products manufacturers American Cast Iron Pipe Company (ACIPCO) and McWane are based in the city.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] Several of the nation's largest steelmakers, including CMC Steel, U.S.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] Steel, and Nucor, also have a major presence in Birmingham.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] In recent years, local steel companies have announced about $100 million worth of investment in expansions and new plants in and around the city.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] Vulcan Materials Company, a major provider of crushed stone, sand, and gravel used in construction, is based in Birmingham.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] In the 1970s and 1980s, Birmingham's economy was transformed by investments in bio-technology and medical research at the University of Alabama at Birmingham (UAB) and its adjacent hospital.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] The UAB Hospital is a Level I trauma center providing health care and breakthrough medical research.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] UAB is now the area's largest employer and the second largest in Alabama with a workforce of about 18,750 as of 2011.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] Health care services providers HealthSouth, Surgical Care Affiliates and Diagnostic Health Corporation are headquartered in the city.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] Caremark Rx was also founded in the city.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] Birmingham is a leading banking center and the headquarters of Regions Financial Corporation.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] Banks with over a 5% market share of deposits in Birmingham are Regions Financial Corporation, PNC Financial Services, Servisfirst Bank, and Wells Fargo.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] Nearly a dozen smaller banks have been headquartered in the Magic City, such as Superior Bancorp and Cadence Bank.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] As of 2009, the finance & banking sector in Birmingham employed 1,870 financial managers, 1,530 loan officers, 680 securities commodities and financial services sales agents, 380 financial analysts, 310 financial examiners, 220 credit analysts, and 130 loan counselors.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] In 2012, Birmingham was the 9th largest banking hub in the United States by the amount of locally headquartered deposits.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] In 2014, Birmingham was the 10th largest banking center.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] Birmingham is a powerhouse of construction and engineering companies, including BE&K, Brasfield & Gorrie, Robins & Morton, and B.L.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] Harbert International which routinely are included in the Engineering News-Record lists of top design and international construction firms.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] Two of the largest soft-drink bottlers in the United States, each with more than $500 million in sales per year, are located in Birmingham.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] The Buffalo Rock Company, founded in 1901, was formerly a maker of just ginger ale, but now it is a major bottler for the Pepsi Cola Company.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] Coca-Cola Bottling Company United, founded in 1902, is the third-largest bottler of Coca-Cola products in the U.S.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] AT&T has a major nexus in Birmingham, supported by a skyscraper downtown as well as several large operational center buildings and a data center.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] Blue Cross and Blue Shield of Alabama, Protective Life, ProAssurance, and Liberty National are headquartered in the city.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] Birmingham has seen a noticeable decrease in the number of Fortune 500 companies headquartered in the city, due to mergers, moves, and buy-outs.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] In 2000, there were ten Fortune 500 companies headquartered in the city, while in 2014 there was only one, Regions Bank.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] Birmingham used to be home to more than thirty publicly traded companies, but in 2011 there were only fifteen.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] This number has increased since, but not significantly.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] Some companies such as Zoe's Kitchen were founded and operated in Birmingham, but have since moved their headquarters.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] Birmingham has rebounded with the growth of companies like Encompass Health Corporation (formerly Healthsouth), Alabama Power Company, Hibbett Sports, Autocar Company, and Books-A-Million.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] Food companies such as Chester's, Jack's, Grapico, Red Diamond, Milo's Hamburgers, and Yogurt Mountain are also based in Birmingham.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] Birmingham's sales tax, which also applies fully to groceries, is 10%, making it the highest tax rate of the nation's 100 largest cities.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] Although Jefferson County's bankruptcy filing was the largest government bankruptcy in U.S. history in 2011, Birmingham remains solvent.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] In 2021, Birmingham's largest public companies by market capitalization were Regions Bank (RF, $14.61 billion), Vulcan Materials (VMC, $8.45 billion), Energen (EGN, $6.47 billion), Protective Life (PL, $5.47 billion), and HealthSouth (HLS, $3.15 billion).
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] All were listed on the New York Stock Exchange.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] Energen sold one of its largest subsidiaries, Alagasco, and Protective Life was bought by Dai-ichi Life and removed from stock exchanges.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] If Alabama Power were considered to be independent of the Southern Company (headquartered in Atlanta), it would be the largest company with more than $5.9 billion in revenue in 2014.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] Birmingham is the cultural and entertainment capital of Alabama with numerous art galleries in the area including the Birmingham Museum of Art, the largest art museum in the Southeast.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] Downtown Birmingham is currently experiencing a cultural and economic rejuvenation, with several new independent shops and restaurants opening in the area.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] Birmingham is also home to the state's major ballet, opera, and symphony orchestra companies such the Alabama Ballet, Alabama Symphony Orchestra, Birmingham Ballet, Birmingham Concert Chorale, and Opera Birmingham.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] Birmingham's nightlife is primarily clustered around Five Points South and Lakeview.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] In addition, a $55-million "Uptown" entertainment district has recently opened adjacent to the BJCC featuring a number of restaurants and a Westin hotel.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] The Cultural Alliance of Greater Birmingham maintains Birmingham365.org, "a one-stop source for finding out what's going on where around" Birmingham.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] The largest is the Birmingham Museum of Art, which is also the largest municipal art museum in the Southeast.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] The area's history museums include the Birmingham Civil Rights Institute, which houses a detailed and emotionally charged narrative exhibit putting Birmingham's history into the context of the U.S.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] It is located on Kelly Ingram Park adjacent to the 16th Street Baptist Church.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] Other history museums include the Southern Museum of Flight, Bessemer Hall of History, Sloss Furnaces National Historic Landmark, Alabama Museum of Health Sciences, and the Arlington Home.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] The Alabama Jazz Hall of Fame is housed in the historic Carver Theatre, and offers exhibits about the numerous notable jazz musicians from the state of Alabama.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] The McWane Science Center is a regional science museum with hands-on science exhibits, temporary exhibitions, and an IMAX dome theater.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] The center also houses a major collection of fossil specimens for use by researchers.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] South of downtown, on Red Mountain, Vulcan Park features the world's largest cast iron statue, depicting Vulcan at his forge.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] Louis Exposition, and erected at Vulcan Park in 1938.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] Birmingham is home to numerous cultural festivals showcasing music, films, and regional heritage.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] Sidewalk Moving Picture Festival brings filmmakers from all over the world to Birmingham to have their films viewed and judged.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] This festival usually is scheduled in late August at eight venues around downtown.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] Screenings are concentrated at the Alabama Theatre.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] Another musical festival is the Taste of 4th Avenue Jazz Festival, presented at the end of August each year, concurrent with the Sidewalk Moving Picture Festival.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] This all day festival features national and local jazz acts.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] In 2007, the festival drew an estimated 6,000 people.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] The Birmingham Folk Festival is an annual event held since 2006.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] In 2009 the festival featured nine local bands and three touring "headliner bands".
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] The Southern Heritage Festival began in the 1960s as a music, arts, and entertainment festival for the African-American community to attract mostly younger demographics.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] Do Dah Day is an annual pet parade held around the end of May.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] The Schaeffer Eye Center Crawfish Boil, an annual music festival event held in May to benefit local charities, always includes an all-star cast of talent.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] It typically draws more than 30,000 spectators for the annual two-day event.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] The annual Greek Festival, a celebration of Greek heritage, culture, and especially cuisine, is a charity fundraiser hosted by the Greek Orthodox Holy Trinity - Holy Cross Cathedral.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] The Greek Festival draws 20,000 patrons annually.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] The Lebanese Food Festival is held at St.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] Magic City Brewfest is an annual festival benefiting local grassroots organization, Free the Hops, and focusing on craft beer.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] Alabama Bound is an annual book and author fair that celebrates Alabama authors and publishers.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] Hosted by the Birmingham Public Library, it is an occasion when fans may meet their favorite authors, buy their books, and hear them read from and talk about their work.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] The Vulcan statue is a cast iron representation of the Roman god of fire, iron, and blacksmiths that is the symbol of Birmingham.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] The statue stands high above the city looking down from a tower at the top of Red Mountain.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] Open to visitors, the tower offers views of the city below.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] The Birmingham Zoo is a large regional zoo with more than 700 animals and an interactive children's zoo.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] The Birmingham Botanical Gardens is a 67-acre (270,000 m2) park displaying a wide variety of plants in interpretive gardens, including formal rose gardens, tropical greenhouses, and a large Japanese garden.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] The facility also includes a white-tablecloth restaurant, meeting rooms, and an extensive reference library.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] It is complemented by Hoover's 30-acre (120,000 m2) Aldridge Botanical Gardens, an ambitious project open since 2002.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] Splash Adventure (formerly VisionLand and Alabama Adventure) in Bessemer serves as the Birmingham area's water and theme park, featuring numerous slides, and water-themed attractions.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] Kelly Ingram Park is the site of notable civil rights protests; the park is adjacent to the historic 16th Street Baptist Church.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] Railroad Park opened in 2010 in downtown Birmingham's Railroad Reservation District.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] Oak Mountain State Park is about 10 miles (16 km) south of Birmingham.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] Red Mountain is one of the southernmost wrinkles in the Appalachian chain, and a scenic drive to the top provides views reminiscent of the Great Smoky Mountains further north.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] To the west of the city is located Tannehill Ironworks Historical State Park, a 1,500-acre (6.1 km2) Civil War site which includes the well-preserved ruins of the Tannehill Iron Furnaces and the John Wesley Hall Grist Mill.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] The Summit is an upscale lifestyle center with many stores and restaurants.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] It is located in Southeast Birmingham off of U.S.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p01] Highway 280, parallel to Interstate 459.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p02] Birmingham has a strong-mayor variant mayor-council form of government, led by a mayor and a nine-member city council.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p02] The current system replaced the previous city commission government in 1962 (primarily as a way to remove Commissioner of Public Safety Eugene "Bull" Connor from power).
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p02] By Alabama law, an issue before a city council must be approved by a two-thirds majority vote (Act No.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p02] Executive powers are held entirely by the Mayor's Office.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p02] Birmingham's current mayor is Randall Woodfin.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p02] Mayor Bell, who previously served as interim Mayor in 1999, won a special election on January 19, 2010, to fill the unexpired term of former Mayor Larry Langford.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p02] Langford was removed from office after being convicted of federal corruption charges on October 28, 2009.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p02] In 1974, Birmingham established a structured network of neighborhood associations and community advisory committees to insure public participation in governmental issues that affect neighborhoods.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p02] Neighborhood associations are routinely consulted on matters related to zoning changes, liquor licenses, economic development, policing and other city services.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p02] Neighborhoods are also granted discretionary funds from the city's budget to use for capital improvements.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p02] Each neighborhood's officers meet with their peers to form Community Advisory Committees which are granted broader powers over city departments.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p02] The presidents of these committees, in turn, form the Citizen's Advisory Board, which meets regularly with the mayor, council, and department heads.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p02] Birmingham is divided into a total of 23 communities, and again into a total of 99 individual neighborhoods with individual neighborhood associations.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p02] The United States Postal Service operates post offices in Birmingham.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p02] The main post office is located at 351 24th Street North in Downtown Birmingham.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p02] Birmingham is also the home of the Social Security Administration's Southeastern Program Service Center.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p02] This center is one of only seven in the United States that process Social Security entitlement claims and payments.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p02] In addition, Birmingham is the home of a branch bank of the Atlanta Federal Reserve Bank.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p02] Birmingham has a crime rate significantly above the national average.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p02] Increasing gang violence and activity have been noted for the spike in crime around the city.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p02] In 2022, Birmingham set a modern record with 144 homicides.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p02] According to a 2023 study, Birmingham leads the nation's largest cities with the highest cost of crime per capita at $11,392.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p02] Its violent crime rate – which includes instances of murder, manslaughter, rape, robbery and aggravated assault – was 1,682 per 100,000 residents.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p02] Its property crime rate – which includes burglary, larceny, and vehicle theft – was notably higher at 4,173 per 100,000 residents.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p02] Also in 2023, *Forbes* ranked Birmingham the second most dangerous city in the United States.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p02] In October 2024, Mayor Woodfin established the Birmingham Crime Commission to better redress the escalating crime crises in the city.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p02] In 2024, Birmingham set a new all-time high murder record with 151 murders in the city.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p02] The downtown district is patrolled by City Action Partnership (CAP), formed in 1995 to increase public perception of safety.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p02] The Birmingham Public Library administers 21 branches throughout the city and it is part of a wider system including another 19 suburban branches in Jefferson County, serving the entire community to provide education and entertainment for all ages.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p02] The city of Birmingham is served by the Birmingham City Schools system.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p02] It is run by the Birmingham Board of Education with a current active enrollment of 30,500 in 62 schools: seven high schools, 13 middle schools, 33 elementary schools, and nine kindergarten-eighth-grade primary schools.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p02] The greater-Birmingham metropolitan area is the home of numerous independent school systems, because there has a been a great deal of fragmentation of educational systems in Alabama, and especially in Jefferson County.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p02] Some of these "school systems" only have three to five schools.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p02] The metropolitan area's three largest school systems are the Jefferson County School System, Birmingham City Schools, and the Shelby County School System.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p02] However, there are many smaller school systems.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p02] The metro area also has three preparatory schools: Saint Rose Academy located in Birmingham proper The Altamont School, also located in Birmingham proper, and Indian Springs School in north Shelby County near Pelham.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p02] Birmingham-Southern College, opened in 1856, closed in May 2024 due to financial troubles.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p02] In 2026, the US Coast Guard opened a training center at the campus of the former Birmingham-Southern College.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p02] Birmingham does not have a major print newspaper since *The Birmingham News* ceased its print edition in 2023.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p02] The newspaper has been awarded two Pulitzer Prizes, in 1991 and 2007.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p02] The *Birmingham Post-Herald*, the city's second daily, published its last issue in 2005.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p02] Other local publications include *The North Jefferson News, The Leeds News*, *The Trussville Tribune* (Trussville, Clay and Pinson), *The Western Star* (Bessemer) and *The Western Tribune* (Bessemer).
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p02] The *Birmingham Times*, a historic African-American newspaper, also is published weekly.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p02] Birmingham is served by the city magazine of the Chamber of Commerce, *Birmingham* magazine.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p02] *The Alabama Baptist*, published weekly in Birmingham, is an entity of the Alabama Baptist Convention.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p02] *Black & White, Weld*, *Birmingham Weekly*, and the *Birmingham Free Press* are some of the free alternative publications that were published in the past (all are now defunct).
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p02] Birmingham is part of the Birmingham–Tuscaloosa–Anniston television market.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p02] The major television affiliates, most of which have their transmitters and studios located on Red Mountain in Birmingham, are WBRC 6 (Fox), WBIQ 10 (PBS), WVTM 13 (NBC), WTTO 21 (CW), WIAT 42 (CBS), WPXH 44 (ION), WBMA-LD 58/68.2 (ABC), and WABM 68 (MyNetworkTV).
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p02] Major broadcasting companies who own stations in the Birmingham market include iHeartMedia, Cox Radio, Cumulus Media, and Crawford Broadcasting.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p02] The *Rick and Bubba* show, which is syndicated to over 25 stations primarily in the Southeast, originates from Birmingham's WZZK-FM.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p02] The Paul Finebaum sports-talk show, also syndicated and carried nationwide on Sirius digital radio, originated from WJOX.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p02] Birmingham is home to EWTN (Eternal Word Television Network), the world's largest Catholic media outlet and religious media network of any kind, broadcasting to about 350 million television households in more than 145 countries and territories, as of 2022.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p02] Before the first structure was built in Birmingham, the plan of the city was laid out over a total of 1,160 acres (4.7 km2) by the directors of the Elyton Land Co.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p02] The streets were numbered from west to east, leaving Twentieth Street to form the central spine of downtown, anchored on the north by Capital Park and stretching into the slopes of Red Mountain to the south.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p02] A "railroad reservation" was granted through the center of the city, running east to west and zoned solely for industrial uses.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p02] As the city grew, bridges and underpasses separated the streets from the railroad bed, lending this central reservation some of the impact of a river (without the pleasant associations of a waterfront).
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p02] From the start, Birmingham's streets and avenues were unusually wide at 80 to 100 feet (24 to 30 m), purportedly to help evacuate unhealthy smoke.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p02] In the early 20th century professional planners helped lay out many of the new industrial settlements and company towns in the Birmingham District, including Corey (now Fairfield) which was developed for the Tennessee Coal, Iron and Railroad Company (subsequently purchased by U.S.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p02] At the same time, a movement to consolidate several neighboring cities gained momentum.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p02] Although local referendums indicated mixed feelings about annexation, the Alabama legislature enacted an expansion of Birmingham's corporate limits that became effective on January 1, 1910.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p02] The Robert Jemison company developed many residential neighborhoods to the south and west of Birmingham which are still renowned for their aesthetic quality.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p02] A 1924 plan for a system of parks, commissioned from the Olmsted Brothers is seeing renewed interest with several significant new parks and greenways under development.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p02] Birmingham officials have approved a City Center Master Plan developed by Urban Design Associates of Pittsburgh, which advocates strongly for more residential development in the downtown area.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p02] The plan also called for a major park over several blocks of the central railroad reservation: Railroad Park, which opened in 2010.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p02] Along with Ruffner Mountain Park and Red Mountain Park, Birmingham ranks first in the United States for public green space per resident.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p02] The water for Birmingham and the intermediate urbanized area is served by the Birmingham Water Works Board (BWWB).
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p02] A public authority that was established in 1951, the BWWB serves all of Jefferson, northern Shelby, western St.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p02] The largest reservoir for BWWB is Lake Purdy, which is located on the Jefferson and Shelby County line, but has several other reservoirs including Bayview Lake in western Jefferson County.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p02] There are plans to pipeline water from Inland Lake in Blount County and Lake Logan Martin, but those plans are on hold indefinitely.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p02] Jefferson County Environmental Services serves the Birmingham metro area with sanitary sewer service.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p02] Sewer rates have increased in recent years after citizens concerned with pollution in area waterways filed a lawsuit that resulted in a federal consent decree to repair an aging sewer system.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p02] Because the estimated cost of the consent decree was approximately three times more than the original estimate, many blame the increased rates on corruption of several Jefferson County officials.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p02] The sewer construction and bond-swap agreements continue to be a controversial topic in the area.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p02] Electric power is provided primarily by Southern Company-subsidiary, Alabama Power.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p02] However, some of the surrounding area such as Bessemer and Cullman are provided by TVA.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p02] Bessemer also operates its own water and sewer system.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p02] Natural gas is provided by Spire, although some metro area cities operate their own natural gas services.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p02] The local telecommunications are provided by AT&T.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p02] Cable television service is provided by Charter Communications.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p02] The city is served by four Interstate Highways, Interstate 20, Interstate 65, Interstate 59, and Interstate 22, as well as a southern bypass expressway Interstate 459, which connects with I-20/59 to the southwest, I-65 to the south, I-20 to the east, and I-59 to the northeast.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p02] Beginning in downtown Birmingham is the "Elton B.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p02] Stephens Expressway"—the *Red Mountain Expressway* to the southeast—which carries both U.S.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p02] Highway 280 to, through, and over Red Mountain.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p02] Interstate 22 was completed in 2012 and connects Birmingham and Memphis, Tennessee.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p02] I-22 connects with I-65 just north of the Birmingham city limits.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p02] Construction has begun on the first segment of I-422, the Birmingham Northern Beltline that will serve the suburbs on the opposite side of Birmingham from I-459.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p02] In the area of metropolitan public transportation, Birmingham is served by the Birmingham-Jefferson County Transit Authority (BJCTA) bus, trolley, and paratransit system, which from 1985 until 2008 was branded the Metro Area Express (MAX).
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p02] BJCTA also operates a "downtown circulator" service called "D A R T" (Downtown Area Runabout Transit), which consists of two routes in the central business district and one in the UAB area.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p02] A bus rapid transit line, named the Birmingham Xpress, was opened in September 2022, running from Woodlawn to Five Points West along the US 11 corridor.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p02] Bus service to other cities is provided by Greyhound Lines.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p02] Megabus also offers bus service to Atlanta and Memphis.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p02] Birmingham is served by the Birmingham–Shuttlesworth International Airport.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p02] This airport serves more than 3 million passengers every year.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p02] With more than 160 flights daily, the airport offers flights to 37 cities across the United States.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p02] Commercial passenger service through Birmingham is provided by United Express, Delta Air Lines/Delta Connection, American Eagle, and Southwest Airlines.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p02] Birmingham was a railroad hub from its founding, and its Beaux-Arts Terminal Station was a major passenger stop for many trains crossing the Southeast until the creation of Amtrak on May 1, 1971, when all but one of Birmingham's passenger trains were eliminated.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p02] The only remaining passenger service is the Amtrak *Crescent*, with one train eastbound and one train westbound daily from the Birmingham Amtrak station.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p02] The *Crescent* route connects Birmingham with Washington, D.C., and points northeast and northwest of there; Greensboro, NC; Charlotte, NC; Greenville, SC; Atlanta, GA; Anniston, AL; Tuscaloosa, AL; Meridian, MS; Hattiesburg, MS; and New Orleans, LA.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p02] Another Amtrak train, the *Floridian*, served Birmingham en route from Chicago to Florida points from November 1971 to October 1979, when it was cancelled for low ridership.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p02] From May 1974 to September 1977, the Auto-Train Corporation operated its eponymous train via Birmingham on its Louisville, Kentucky to Sanford, Florida route.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p02] However, Birmingham was not a passenger stop for the *Auto-Train*, merely a crew-change point.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p02] The Auto-Train Corporation went out of business in 1981, but since 1983, Amtrak has operated another *Auto Train* (no hyphen) between Lorton, Virginia, and Sanford; it does not enter Alabama.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p02] Beginning in October 1989, Amtrak's *Gulf Breeze* was a section of the *Crescent* that split from the *Crescent* at Birmingham and ran to Mobile, stopping at several intermediate points.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p02] The state of Alabama shared the operating costs with Amtrak; however, due to dismally low ridership, the *Gulf Breeze* was discontinued in April 1995.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p02] Birmingham is served by three major freight railroad companies, the Norfolk Southern Company, CSX Transportation, and BNSF Railway, all of which have major railroad yards in the metro area.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p02] Smaller regional railroads such as the Alabama Warrior Railway and the Birmingham Southern Railroad also serve customers in Birmingham.
[src:jim-clinton/birmingham-alabama-p02] Birmingham's Sister Cities program is overseen by the Birmingham Sister Cities Commission.
[src:jim-clinton/brooklyn-atlantics] The **Atlantic Base Ball Club** of Brooklyn ("Atlantic" or the "Brooklyn Atlantics") was baseball's first champion and its first dynasty.
[src:jim-clinton/brooklyn-atlantics] The team was also the first baseball club to visit the White House in 1865 at the invitation of President Andrew Johnson.
[src:jim-clinton/brooklyn-atlantics] Established on August 14, 1855, Atlantic became a founding member of the National Association of Base Ball Players, the amateur sport's first governing body, in 1857.
[src:jim-clinton/brooklyn-atlantics] (There were no professional clubs at the time.) In 1859, with a record of 11 wins and 1 loss, Atlantic emerged as the recognized champions of baseball.
[src:jim-clinton/brooklyn-atlantics] Atlantic held the championship through the 1861 season, albeit in controversial fashion.
[src:jim-clinton/brooklyn-atlantics] In a third and deciding game with Excelsior of Brooklyn, Excelsior was leading 8–6 and had men on base, but was forced to withdraw by a rowdy crowd of Atlantic partisans and gamblers.
[src:jim-clinton/brooklyn-atlantics] The game was declared a draw, and the championship retained by Atlantic.
[src:jim-clinton/brooklyn-atlantics] Atlantic held the championship again through the 1861 season, which was shortened due to the American Civil War, before finally surrendering it to archrival Eckford of Brooklyn in 1862.
[src:jim-clinton/brooklyn-atlantics] Atlantic recaptured the pennant in 1866 with a season record of twenty wins, no defeats, and a single tie as the only blemish on its record.
[src:jim-clinton/brooklyn-atlantics] Atlantic went undefeated in 1865 with an 18–0 record, sweeping series against chief rivals Mutual of New York and Athletic of Philadelphia.
[src:jim-clinton/brooklyn-atlantics] Great players of this era included Joe Start, Dickey Pearce, Charlie Smith, Fred Crane, and Tom Pratt.
[src:jim-clinton/brooklyn-atlantics] Atlantic's 36-game winning streak was finally broken in June, 1866 by Irvington, NJ.
[src:jim-clinton/brooklyn-atlantics] Atlantic retained the pennant that year by splitting a two-game series with Athletic of Philadelphia and declining to schedule a series with Union of Morrisania.
[src:jim-clinton/brooklyn-atlantics] Atlantic did surrender the title to Union in 1867.
[src:jim-clinton/brooklyn-atlantics] When Atlantic defeated Eckford to regain the pennant in 1869, Atlantic had already lost to the Cincinnati Red Stockings.
[src:jim-clinton/brooklyn-atlantics] This allowed Atlantic to claim the championship over the undefeated Cincinnati club under the "challenge" format of the National Association of Base Ball Players, which resembled modern boxing championship rules rather than a league or tournament format.
[src:jim-clinton/brooklyn-atlantics] This outcome undoubtedly contributed to the tremendous anticipation when Cincinnati came to Brooklyn with an 89-game winning streak to meet the Atlantics on June 14, 1870 at Atlantic's home Capitoline Grounds.
[src:jim-clinton/brooklyn-atlantics] An estimated crowd of 15,000 paid 50 cents a piece to see Atlantic win 8–7 in extra innings in one of the most significant games in baseball history.
[src:jim-clinton/brooklyn-atlantics] Atlantic surrendered the title later in the year, though, to Mutual.
[src:jim-clinton/brooklyn-atlantics] After the 1865 season, the Atlantics became the first baseball team to visit the White House.
[src:jim-clinton/brooklyn-atlantics] Arthur Gorman, one of the founders of the Washington Nationals Base Ball Club and an acquaintance of President Andrew Johnson, organized a tournament featuring his team, the Athletic Base Ball Club of Philadelphia and the Atlantics.
[src:jim-clinton/brooklyn-atlantics] Philadelphia refused to play in the final game as they would not receive any of the gate revenue and left.
[src:jim-clinton/brooklyn-atlantics] Having known President Johnson since his days as a page in the United States Senate, Gorman offered to take the visiting team to the White House to meet the President.
[src:jim-clinton/brooklyn-atlantics] Brooklyn accepted and visited on August 30, 1865.
[src:jim-clinton/brooklyn-atlantics] A daguerreotype of the Atlantics presenting an official team jersey to the President bearing the number “65” is on display at the National Baseball Hall of Fame in Cooperstown, New York.
[src:jim-clinton/brooklyn-atlantics] Atlantic had been among the first clubs to declare themselves professional when allowed to do so in 1869.
[src:jim-clinton/brooklyn-atlantics] However, when the major professional clubs formed the National Association of Professional Base Ball Players in 1871, Atlantic declined to field a team.
[src:jim-clinton/brooklyn-atlantics] As a result, their best players, including George Zettlein, Bob Ferguson, Joe Start and Lip Pike, jumped to other clubs.
[src:jim-clinton/brooklyn-atlantics] When Atlantic did join the professional circuit in 1872, it was unable to reestablish itself as a leading club, suffering losing records in each of its four seasons in the league.
[src:jim-clinton/brooklyn-atlantics] Atlantic was not invited to join the National League when that circuit was formed in 1876, but continued to play an independent schedule until at least 1882.
[src:jim-clinton/brooklyn-atlantics] A remnant Atlantic was invited to join the upstart American Association in 1882 but failed to satisfy the requirements for doing so.
[src:jim-clinton/brooklyn-atlantics] For many years afterwards, the term *Atlantic batting* referred to a big inning, especially late in the game.
[src:jim-clinton/brooklyn-atlantics] Source for season records: Wright (2000) has published records for dozens of NABBP teams each season, relying on a mix of game and season records in contemporary newspapers and guides.
[src:jim-clinton/brooklyn-atlantics] Dozens of leading clubs by number of matches are included, as are many others.
[src:jim-clinton/brooklyn-atlantics] The records do not consistently cover either all games played or all championship matches between NABBP members.
[src:jim-clinton/brooklyn-eckfords] Formally organized on June 27, 1855, the **Eckford Base Ball Club** was named for shipbuilder Henry Eckford whose base of operations from the late 1790s until the early 1830s was Brooklyn, New York.
[src:jim-clinton/brooklyn-eckfords] He designed many American warships that participated in the War of 1812.
[src:jim-clinton/brooklyn-eckfords] The team's first president was Frank Pidgeon, who was one of Eckford's founding members.
[src:jim-clinton/brooklyn-eckfords] From the sports page of Chicago's *Daily Inter Ocean* newspaper, December 20, 1879, p.
[src:jim-clinton/brooklyn-eckfords] 3: "Peter Tostevin, whose name was identified with the early history of the once famous Eckford Club of Brooklyn, N.Y., died in that city Dec.
[src:jim-clinton/brooklyn-eckfords] Eckford was one of 16 participants in the 1857 convention, all from modern New York City.
[src:jim-clinton/brooklyn-eckfords] There the pioneer New York Knickerbockers essentially transferred baseball governance to the leading clubs as a group, so the event is traditionally considered the birthday of the National Association of Base Ball Players and the participants are considered the NABBP charter members.
[src:jim-clinton/brooklyn-eckfords] Today the Eckford club and its teams are commonly called "the **Brooklyn Eckfords**".
[src:jim-clinton/brooklyn-eckfords] "Brooklyn" in the team name is a later development, matching the later convention that a club or team should be named for a locale or region that it represents.
[src:jim-clinton/brooklyn-eckfords] The Eckfords never represented Brooklyn.
[src:jim-clinton/brooklyn-eckfords] First, they did not survive to the era of exclusive territories, sometimes called "sports franchising", which the new National League instituted in 1876.
[src:jim-clinton/brooklyn-eckfords] Second, Brooklyn was populous enough to maintain several strong teams and support the construction of two enclosed ballparks during the amateur days when few players migrated to baseball jobs.
[src:jim-clinton/brooklyn-eckfords] Third, New York and Brooklyn had the early start, as the hotbeds where multiple clubs developed prior to cooperation.
[src:jim-clinton/brooklyn-eckfords] At the first convention, eight of 16 clubs were based in Brooklyn; three years later, it was 20 of 59.
[src:jim-clinton/brooklyn-eckfords] For all these reasons, When the NABBP permitted open professionalism in 1869, Eckford and Atlantic among dozens of Brooklyn members were both viable in following that route, and in 1872 they both joined the National Association league for its second season.
[src:jim-clinton/brooklyn-eckfords] In winter 1871, Eckford did not participate in founding the National Association of Professional Base Ball Players (NA), nor did it enter a team in that first professional league season.
[src:jim-clinton/brooklyn-eckfords] The team did win about half of about thirty games against NA opponents, including some late summer games picked up after the Fort Wayne Kekiongas went out of business.
[src:jim-clinton/brooklyn-eckfords] For 1872 Eckford paid the $10 entry fee and assembled a team but it was a woefully weak one that lost all of its 11 games played to July 9, with average score 5-22.
[src:jim-clinton/brooklyn-eckfords] Five of the league's eleven teams would drop out by late August but the Eckfords survived.
[src:jim-clinton/brooklyn-eckfords] Fortified by seven players from Troy and Cleveland, including both pitchers and three other regulars, they returned to the field August 9.
[src:jim-clinton/brooklyn-eckfords] The strengthened team won three of 18 games with average score 5-9.
[src:jim-clinton/brooklyn-eckfords] The old amateur rivals Atlantic and Eckford won only four and three of their last 18 games in the much stronger six-team league from mid-August.
[src:jim-clinton/brooklyn-eckfords] In four matches they each won two and scored 37 runs.
[src:jim-clinton/brooklyn-eckfords] They may have been equals on the field once again, but Eckford went out of business while Atlantic improved its team and moved in to share the Union Grounds with the Mutuals for the last three National Association seasons.
